                            <comment id="13068580" author="stack" created="Wed, 20 Jul 2011 19:38:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yeah, we need this bad with a while.  We have &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-1730&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-1730&lt;/a&gt; which seems to be the same thing.  What you think Dhruba (Maybe you just want to address this small piece of the bigger 1730 issue).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13068708" author="dhruba" created="Wed, 20 Jul 2011 23:23:44 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yes, this looks like a subset of &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-1730&quot; title=&quot;Near-instantaneous online schema and table state updates&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-1730&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;HBASE-1730&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. I will close this one and continue the design discussion on &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-1730&quot; title=&quot;Near-instantaneous online schema and table state updates&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-1730&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;HBASE-1730&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13068709" author="dhruba" created="Wed, 20 Jul 2011 23:24:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;duplicate of &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-1730&quot; title=&quot;Near-instantaneous online schema and table state updates&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-1730&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;HBASE-1730&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13068716" author="tlipcon" created="Wed, 20 Jul 2011 23:33:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;would it make sense to reconsider our conflation of locality groups and column families at this point as well, while we&apos;re &quot;in there&quot; changing stuff around? or too much work?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13068730" author="dhruba" created="Wed, 20 Jul 2011 23:57:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Todd, can you pl explain &quot;would it make sense to reconsider our conflation of locality groups and column families&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="13068826" author="stack" created="Thu, 21 Jul 2011 06:28:35 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;@Dhruba For &apos;locality groups&apos;, see the big table paper.  Locality groups are made of one or more column families.  In the schema you designated what cfs were in what locality groups.  Then, apparently, all cf members of a locality group were colocated on disk.  Also, you could change what cfs belonged to what locality groups.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;HBase doesn&apos;t have notion of locality groups. It just has cfs (We &apos;conflate&apos; locality groups and column families &amp;#8211; or we just don&apos;t do locality groups).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;@Todd I think it likely too much work.  Should we support locality groups?   On the fly we&apos;d support moving cfs between locality groups?&lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="13068833" author="tlipcon" created="Thu, 21 Jul 2011 06:46:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yes, I meant locality groups as Stack described above.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The advantages of allowing multiple column families to be in a single locality group are:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul class=&quot;alternate&quot; type=&quot;square&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;people often want a way of grouping together sets of columns &quot;logically&quot; - you can certainly use a prefix here, but the CF already seems like a natural prefix&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;often times (especially if you&apos;re new to the data model) it&apos;s not clear what the correct grouping of columns should be for your access patterns. Putting the different types of data in different CFs, and then later being able to migrate CFs between locality groups allows you to do the logical groupings up front, and then modify the physical groupings as the access patterns become more clear later.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;BigTable has some properties that apply to column families and others that apply to locality groups. For example, compression and block size are physical properties and thus apply to the LG. TTL and version retention are logical properties and thus would apply to a column family. I&apos;ve often seen cases where two types of data are stored together in a CF for locality reasons, but they really should have different TTL policies. Another example would be schema information for use by a coprocessor that provides a secondary index.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="13068835" author="tlipcon" created="Thu, 21 Jul 2011 06:47:52 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;On the fly we&apos;d support moving cfs between locality groups?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As I understand it, this is done in BigTable only when new files are written. So, if a CF is moved from one LG to another, reads continue to look at both LGs, while any new flushes/compaction results put the new data in the new LG. Once all data has been re-written, the migration is complete.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
